title: Samsung’s Wireless Frame Pro TV Is a Disaster (And I’m Stuck With It)
description: Samsung's new $2,200 Wireless Frame Pro TV is AWFUL! Watch it implode under latency, bugs, and edge‑lit lies. Save on the Rhinoshield AirX at checkout using code "SNAZZYLABS" - https://url.rhinoshield.io/SNAZZYLABS Follow Snazzy Labs on Twitter - https://twitter.com/snazzylabs   Follow me on Bluesky - https://snazzy.fm/UW Follow me on Threads - https://snazzy.fm/XV Follow me on Mastodon - https://snazzy.fm/NN Follow me on Instagram - https://instagram.com/snazzyq  In this Samsung Frame Pro review, I explain why the $2,200 “wireless” TV is a disaster: the Wireless One Connect box causes latency, stutters, and constant disconnects, the micro‑HDMI 2.1 port lacks eARC/ARC for soundbars, Wi‑Fi 7/6GHz interference breaks stability, and HDMI‑CEC mangles Art Mode power behavior. Despite the matte panel and convincing Art Mode, the edge‑lit “Neo QLED powered by mini‑LED” display delivers poor contrast, vertical banding, smeary night scenes, and unhinged default picture settings—with no Dolby Vision. Software is painfully slow (TV Plus bloat), setup is infuriating (mounting/stud issues, cable routing), and even Samsung’s S801D soundbar drops audio over Wi‑Fi, forcing a lower‑quality Bluetooth fallback. If you want a main TV, buy an OLED; for an art TV, cheaper Hisense/TCL models are better. Bottom line: Samsung Frame Pro looks like wall art, but as a wireless TV it’s laggy, unreliable, and wildly overpriced.  0:00 - This is the worst TV I've ever owned 0:29 - What's the point of "Frame"-style TVs? 2:39 - How Is It Wireless? 4:15 - Installation HELL 6:45 - eARC sound bar support is ABYSMAL 8:41 - Wireless TV? Wireless sound bar! (it's bad) 10:28 - WiFi 7 will absolutely jack up this TV 11:30 - Software is laughably bad—I've never used a worse TV 16:15 - Hardware is also bad: Apple TV issues, latency, stutter 18:42 - Samsung literally false advertised mini LED—picture quality stinks 21:27 - But this TV is about ART—so how is it?? 23:22 - "Pro" this TV is not—especially at night 24:04 - Do not buy this TV—it's garbage

title: The Unstoppable Rise Of LG TVs (There's No Catching Up)
description: 💡 Turn any idea into a production-ready app or website by describing it to AI. Dream it, and Lindy builds it from coding to QA. Try Lindy today using my link 👉🏻 https://go.lindy.ai/logically-answered   In the early 2010s, OLED was a joke. Too fragile, too expensive, and impossible to scale. Everyone dropped it except LG. Fast forward to today, and LG owns over half the global OLED market. They even make panels for Samsung and Sony. So what did LG see that everyone else missed? Back in the 2000s, the TV world was all Plasma and LCD. Plasma had the best picture but came with heat, power, and burn-in issues. LCDs were cheap, efficient, and “good enough.” While everyone chased scale, LG doubled down on quality. They bought Kodak’s OLED patents, poured billions into R&D, and invented WRGB OLED to cut costs. For years, it looked like financial suicide. But when Netflix, gaming, and home theaters exploded, OLED became the gold standard. By 2016, LG had perfected manufacturing, and by 2017, the C7 OLED changed everything. Competitors mocked OLED, then bought LG panels anyway. Now, LG Display supplies Samsung, Sony, and nearly every major brand. The bet no one believed in became the tech no one could live without. title: Best TV of 2025 (Shootout): LG G5 vs Samsung S95F vs Sony BRAVIA 8 II vs Panasonic Z95B
description: Our 2025 TV shootout between the LG G5 & Panasonic Z95B 4-stack WOLED TVs + Samsung S95F & Sony BRAVIA 8 II QD-OLEDs.  All competing TVs were 55 inches in screen size, and were calibrated in SDR and HDR modes to the common standards used within the film and broadcast industry, perceptually matched to a Sony BVM-HX3110 dual-layer LCD mastering monitor capable of reaching a peak brightness of 4000 nits.  All the TVs were masked, so the 6 video professional & sole enthusiast judges didn't know which TV was which when scoring different picture attributes.  00:00 Intro 00:21 Near-black 00:57 Colours 02:12 HDR 03:38 Motion 04:31 Uniformity 05:02 Video processing 05:52 Bright room 06:14 Out of The Box 06:48 Best Home Cinema TV 07:33 Best Living Room TV 11:23 Best TV of 2025 12:37 Shootout format  The judges were (in alphabetical order by surname):  1. Zeb Chadfield, Founder & Chief Vision Officer at The Finish Line 2. Maciej Koper, Professional Calibrator & Reviewer at Wybierz.tv & Choose.tv 3. Ian Lowe, ex-Dolby Vision Post Production 4. James Meredith, Technical Director & Co-Founder at Netvio 5. Julian Nelson, Head of Post Production & Co-Founder at Residence Pictures 6. Luis Pinhao, Imaging Engineer at Cinelab Ltd 7. Robert Walia, TV enthusiast    The results neither represent the opinions or views of individual judges, nor do they constitute the endorsement of any particular TV brand, since the judges didn’t even know which TV was which throughout the voting process.  Thanks to award-winning UK electrical retailer Crampton & Moore for supplying the TVs & organising the shootout. If you're interested in purchasing a new TV, even if it's not the LG G5, Panasonic Z95B, Samsung S95F or Sony XR80M2, please support this channel by considering buying from Crampton & Moore... call 01423 569249 or email david.conner@cramptonandmoore.co.uk  Thanks to professional AV mounting specialist B-Tech International Group for loaning the BTF841 universal dual-stack floor stands for the shootout. For more information, please visit: https://www.btechavmounts.com/  Thanks to content distribution specialist Netvio for loaning the 8x8 matrix for the shootout. Netvio provide a wide range of high quality, Ultra High Definition HDMI distribution products using several different technologies including Fibre, AV over IP and HDBaseT, with unique AV control apps, control system drivers and software. You can find more information at https://www.netvio.co.uk  Thanks to HDMI 2.1 cable manufacturer Zeskit for supplying all the HDMI cables used at the shootout. title: 7 Things I HATE about Samsung Frame TV PRO (FULL Review)
description: **Price it/Learn more here: https://amzn.to/475cn7k **   I've reviewed nearly every iteration of the Samsung Frame TV, since it was first released back in 2017, and I know a lot about it… and since millions of you have seen those videos I decided it was time to buy this 2025 Pro version and test it out for myself so you can see if it might be worth it for you. Particularly because Samsung now has more competition in this art-TV category.  So what's new with the Samsung The Frame TV Pro, is it better than previous versions or is Samsung just jumping on the Pro Label bandwagon? What are the overall pros and cons and can I recommend it for you?  I bought the 65-inch Frame TV for my living room.  Join my channel for Exclusive members-only perks: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCDGqNf14HSF9v8e-Qmp7VXA/join  ~Get My Newsletter: http://www.techgadgetscanada.com/newsletter-signup/  **May contain Affiliate Links: My YouTube channel is supported by the viewers. Occasionally I will include affiliate links in my reviews. This allows you to get more info easily, and I also may get a small commission from the click, which helps me keep the blog and this YouTube channel running. If you choose to use an affiliate link I thank you greatly for supporting my content. There's no obligation or cost to you for using these links. As an Amazon Associate I earn from qualifying purchases.   I’ll quickly touch on the basics of a Frame TV for those who might be newer to the concept. In essence this is a TV that doesn't look like a TV; when it's not in use playing ultra high definition 4K video and TV shows, the screen shows highly realistic and super high resolution artworks. Thanks to a special coating on the screen, you're not simply getting a screensaver, you're actually getting a display that melts into the background and genuinely becomes part of your decor. Customizable wooden frames, and an included flush mount with no-gap lets you make the screen disappear into your space, or pop like real artwork.   What’s new? I'm going to quickly cover what the new features are with the Frame Pro version. For starters the one connect box is now wireless… and I'll explain in more detail what that means, momentarily.   The display panel technology has also been updated; technically speaking the regular frame uses a QLED panel, while the pro version uses ‘’Neo QLED with Mini LED backlighting’…   Refresh rate on the pro version is also higher at 144hz (the regular Frame is 120hz) meaning it should be better able to handle faster action sequences and potentially even gaming. Samsung is also touting ‘enhanced AI features’… but I'll see what that actually translates to in practice. Samsung The Frame Pro is available in only 3 sizes: 65-inch, 75-inch, and 85-inch.   That's what's new with this version. Now let's get to what it's like to own one…  Set up & Installation If you're new to this TV the installation is not all that difficult. If you have an older model you might be disappointed to find that—Frustration Number one— the bracket has been altered just enough to make it slightly incompatible with the new Pro version, so no re-using the old mounts. Previously known as the ‘no gap wall mount’, you'll affix two mounting brackets onto your wall and a paper template included in the box makes this easier. Then attach to metal loops to the back of the TV. The loops will hang on the wall brackets to provide a stable yet flat support system for the TV that also offers a small amount of adjustability so you can get things square. Then you need to plug the TV in to power.  We had the TV installed and mounted in about an hour. Once the heavy lifting is done you'll plug in the new One Connect Box to power also, and get the TV onto your Wi-Fi network. From there you'll need to set up a handful of accounts and permissions and logins but you'll largely be ready to go.    ‘Wireless’ One Connect Box The most significant update in the Pro model is the new Wireless One Connect Box that comes with your Frame TV Pro. But this isn’t what it seems… and don’t let what you can’t see here in my set up fool you…   With the Samsung Frame TV Pro here, Samsung will tell you it made a huge leap for all of us, by getting rid of the translucent wire completely with their new Wireless One Connect box. But the joke is on all of us because—Frustration Number 2— while you don't have a thin translucent wire running from the One Connect box to the TV, you do still have to get power to the TV and for that Samsung has supplied a fat white power cable, and good luck hiding that without conduit inside the wall. Or…Here’s hoping you're one of those lucky few who has a power outlet high up on the wall where you can connect this to keep it out of view.
comment_text_summary: 댓글들은 주로 Frame Pro TV에 대한 사용자 경험과 리뷰에 대한 반응을 담고 있으며, 긍정적인 사용 경험과 부정적인 문제점들이 혼재되어 있습니다. 일부 사용자는 TV의 전원 요구 사항과 연결 문제에 대한 우려를 표명하고 있습니다.

title: Samsung’s Wireless Frame Pro TV Is a Disaster (And I’m Stuck With It)
description: Samsung's new $2,200 Wireless Frame Pro TV is AWFUL! Watch it implode under latency, bugs, and edge‑lit lies. Save on the Rhinoshield AirX at checkout using code "SNAZZYLABS" - https://url.rhinoshield.io/SNAZZYLABS Follow Snazzy Labs on Twitter - https://twitter.com/snazzylabs   Follow me on Bluesky - https://snazzy.fm/UW Follow me on Threads - https://snazzy.fm/XV Follow me on Mastodon - https://snazzy.fm/NN Follow me on Instagram - https://instagram.com/snazzyq  In this Samsung Frame Pro review, I explain why the $2,200 “wireless” TV is a disaster: the Wireless One Connect box causes latency, stutters, and constant disconnects, the micro‑HDMI 2.1 port lacks eARC/ARC for soundbars, Wi‑Fi 7/6GHz interference breaks stability, and HDMI‑CEC mangles Art Mode power behavior. Despite the matte panel and convincing Art Mode, the edge‑lit “Neo QLED powered by mini‑LED” display delivers poor contrast, vertical banding, smeary night scenes, and unhinged default picture settings—with no Dolby Vision. Software is painfully slow (TV Plus bloat), setup is infuriating (mounting/stud issues, cable routing), and even Samsung’s S801D soundbar drops audio over Wi‑Fi, forcing a lower‑quality Bluetooth fallback. If you want a main TV, buy an OLED; for an art TV, cheaper Hisense/TCL models are better. Bottom line: Samsung Frame Pro looks like wall art, but as a wireless TV it’s laggy, unreliable, and wildly overpriced.  0:00 - This is the worst TV I've ever owned 0:29 - What's the point of "Frame"-style TVs? 2:39 - How Is It Wireless? 4:15 - Installation HELL 6:45 - eARC sound bar support is ABYSMAL 8:41 - Wireless TV? Wireless sound bar! (it's bad) 10:28 - WiFi 7 will absolutely jack up this TV 11:30 - Software is laughably bad—I've never used a worse TV 16:15 - Hardware is also bad: Apple TV issues, latency, stutter 18:42 - Samsung literally false advertised mini LED—picture quality stinks 21:27 - But this TV is about ART—so how is it?? 23:22 - "Pro" this TV is not—especially at night 24:04 - Do not buy this TV—it's garbage

title: The Unstoppable Rise Of LG TVs (There's No Catching Up)
description: 💡 Turn any idea into a production-ready app or website by describing it to AI. Dream it, and Lindy builds it from coding to QA. Try Lindy today using my link 👉🏻 https://go.lindy.ai/logically-answered   In the early 2010s, OLED was a joke. Too fragile, too expensive, and impossible to scale. Everyone dropped it except LG. Fast forward to today, and LG owns over half the global OLED market. They even make panels for Samsung and Sony. So what did LG see that everyone else missed? Back in the 2000s, the TV world was all Plasma and LCD. Plasma had the best picture but came with heat, power, and burn-in issues. LCDs were cheap, efficient, and “good enough.” While everyone chased scale, LG doubled down on quality. They bought Kodak’s OLED patents, poured billions into R&D, and invented WRGB OLED to cut costs. For years, it looked like financial suicide. But when Netflix, gaming, and home theaters exploded, OLED became the gold standard. By 2016, LG had perfected manufacturing, and by 2017, the C7 OLED changed everything. Competitors mocked OLED, then bought LG panels anyway. Now, LG Display supplies Samsung, Sony, and nearly every major brand. The bet no one believed in became the tech no one could live without. title: Best TV of 2025 (Shootout): LG G5 vs Samsung S95F vs Sony BRAVIA 8 II vs Panasonic Z95B
description: Our 2025 TV shootout between the LG G5 & Panasonic Z95B 4-stack WOLED TVs + Samsung S95F & Sony BRAVIA 8 II QD-OLEDs.  All competing TVs were 55 inches in screen size, and were calibrated in SDR and HDR modes to the common standards used within the film and broadcast industry, perceptually matched to a Sony BVM-HX3110 dual-layer LCD mastering monitor capable of reaching a peak brightness of 4000 nits.  All the TVs were masked, so the 6 video professional & sole enthusiast judges didn't know which TV was which when scoring different picture attributes.  00:00 Intro 00:21 Near-black 00:57 Colours 02:12 HDR 03:38 Motion 04:31 Uniformity 05:02 Video processing 05:52 Bright room 06:14 Out of The Box 06:48 Best Home Cinema TV 07:33 Best Living Room TV 11:23 Best TV of 2025 12:37 Shootout format  The judges were (in alphabetical order by surname):  1. Zeb Chadfield, Founder & Chief Vision Officer at The Finish Line 2. Maciej Koper, Professional Calibrator & Reviewer at Wybierz.tv & Choose.tv 3. Ian Lowe, ex-Dolby Vision Post Production 4. James Meredith, Technical Director & Co-Founder at Netvio 5. Julian Nelson, Head of Post Production & Co-Founder at Residence Pictures 6. Luis Pinhao, Imaging Engineer at Cinelab Ltd 7. Robert Walia, TV enthusiast    The results neither represent the opinions or views of individual judges, nor do they constitute the endorsement of any particular TV brand, since the judges didn’t even know which TV was which throughout the voting process.  Thanks to award-winning UK electrical retailer Crampton & Moore for supplying the TVs & organising the shootout. If you're interested in purchasing a new TV, even if it's not the LG G5, Panasonic Z95B, Samsung S95F or Sony XR80M2, please support this channel by considering buying from Crampton & Moore... call 01423 569249 or email david.conner@cramptonandmoore.co.uk  Thanks to professional AV mounting specialist B-Tech International Group for loaning the BTF841 universal dual-stack floor stands for the shootout. For more information, please visit: https://www.btechavmounts.com/  Thanks to content distribution specialist Netvio for loaning the 8x8 matrix for the shootout. Netvio provide a wide range of high quality, Ultra High Definition HDMI distribution products using several different technologies including Fibre, AV over IP and HDBaseT, with unique AV control apps, control system drivers and software. You can find more information at https://www.netvio.co.uk  Thanks to HDMI 2.1 cable manufacturer Zeskit for supplying all the HDMI cables used at the shootout.
